column2: Could Be Added To Ark ETFs#https://finance.yahoo.com/news/7-stocks-fit-cathie-woods-173506543.html#https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/vcjyv_WgYYjOZBuIQJ_.3Q--~B/aD00MDA7dz02MDA7YXBwaWQ9eXRhY2h5b24-/https://media.zenfs.com/en/Benzinga/3900bd159fd601be8d861979cc94cc41#en#0.3612#finance.yahoo.com#Ark Funds held its annual Big Ideas event recently and shared 15 themes to watch for 2021 and the future.  Ark ETFs include the Ark Innovation ETF (NYSE: ARKK)
column3: Ark Next Generation Internet ETF (NYSE: ARKW)
column4: Ark Genomic Revolution ETF (BATS: ARKG)
column5: Ark Fintech Innotvation ETF (NYSE: ARKF) and Ark Autonomous Technology & Robotics ETF (BATS: ARKQ).  The themes presented by Cathie Wood and her team could provide hints at which companies in the future could be included in the ETFs.  Here is a look at some potential candidates based on the Ark Funds 2021 Big Ideas.  1.  Desktop Metal: 3D printing company Desktop Metal (NYSE: DM) fits the profile of the 3D printing theme revolutionizing manufacturing.  Desktop Metal is included in the 3D Printing ETF (BATS: PRNT) and based on the comments from Ark could soon be added to additional ETFs from the company.  Chamath Palihapitiya is an investor in the company.  The so-called SPAC King calls Desktop Metal a leader in the new era of printing and said it can work with automotive and aerospace companies to create parts with less weight.  This production scale is considered the holy grail.  Ford Motor Company (NYSE: F) is another investor in the company.  2.  AST & Science: Going public via a SPAC deal with New Providence Acquisition Corp (NASDAQ: NPA)
column6: AST & Science is bringing its ambitious plans for 5G from space to the public markets.  The company seems like a perfect fit for Ark’s Big Idea of orbital aerospace.  Under this idea
column7: Ark calls for satellite broadband to see strong revenue growth in the future.  AST is targeting the $1 trillion global mobile wireless service market.  AST said that 51% of the global population does not have mobile broadband.  The company’s plans call for launching over 180 satellites to bring 5G access to customers with a goal of hitting 373 million subscribers by 2027.  Related Link: Cathie Wood Increases Teladoc Holdings Across Ark ETFs 3.  Virgin Galactic: News that Ark Funds was launching a Space ETF sent names of space related companies like Virgin Galactic Holdings (NYSE: SPCE) higher.  Virgin Galactic seems could be the perfect fit for the Ark Big Idea of orbital aerospace
column8: which includes hypersonic flight.  4.  SoFi: Wood has added several SPACs to the Ark ETFs and the next one added could be Social Capital Hedosophia Holdings VCorp (NYSE: IPOE).  The Palihapitiya-backed SPAC is taking SoFi public.  The Big Ideas presentation calls for digital wallets to be a $4. 6 trillion opportunity.  SoFi is singled out as an example in the North American region.  5.  Brooks Automation: One Big Idea theme is automation
column9: a sector that Brooks Automation (NASDAQ: BRKS) fits into.  Brooks Automation powers the semiconductor and life sciences sectors with robots and automations.  With the focus on automation and robotics across several Ark funds
column10: this could be a stock worth watching for investors.  6.  EHang Holdings: Autonomous aerial vehicle company EHang Holdings (NASDAQ: EH) is up over 450% in the last year.  The company has become one of the ways for investors to get exposure to the growing passenger transport and logistics for urban air mobility.  With the focus on drone delivery as a 2021 Big Idea
column11: Ehang could be on the radar of Ark Funds.  7.  Natera: Natera Inc (NASDAQ: NTRA) is the global leader in cell-free DNA testing focusing on women’s health and oncology.  The company could find itself fitting into the Ark Funds Big Idea of long road sequencing. 2021-02-03 05:50:36#business#Musk Keeps Sparring With Regulators as Biden Builds Cabinet#https://finance.yahoo.com/news/musk-keeps-sparring-regulators-biden-001053337.html#https://s.yimg.com/uu/api/res/1.2/UsFTtHmWJ7d0xt4ImjGZ9g--~B/aD0xMzMzO3c9MjAwMDthcHBpZD15dGFjaHlvbg--/https://media.zenfs.com/en/bloomberg_markets_842/1831d57f0d1ea066f0896702d1ba614c#en#0.0#finance.yahoo.com#(Bloomberg) -- Elon Musk has a long history of run-ins with the local
column2: state and federal officials who oversee his growing empires at Tesla Inc.  and SpaceX.  The world’s richest person shows no signs of changing his ways as U. S.  President Joe Biden takes office and bolsters the regulatory agencies defanged by his predecessor. In the past week alone
column3: Musk has tangled with the Federal Aviation Administration over a December rocket test flight that ended in flames and begrudgingly agreed to recall some Tesla cars at highway-safety officials’ urging.  And while he announced Tuesday he was taking a break from Twitter -- the platform that previously got him fined by the Securities and Exchange Commission -- Musk had already used his favorite social-media megaphone in the preceding days to roil stocks of companies from Etsy Inc.  to Shopify Inc.  during a retail-trading frenzy. The potential for more conflict is building as Biden works to confirm his cabinet secretaries and reinvigorate agencies following the Donald Trump era.  Democratic administrations have historically been tougher on industry regulation
column4: and Musk’s empire intersects with government oversight of automobiles
column5: spaceflight
column7: telecommunications and medical equipment. In a series of comments on Tuesday
column8: the FAA said that Musk’s Space Exploration Technologies Corp.  had ignored the agency back on Dec.  9 to go ahead with a test launch of its massive Starship rocket -- a test that ended in a blazing fireball when the prototype malfunctioned on landing.  The FAA said it had turned down SpaceX ’s request to exceed the maximum public risk for that launch
column9: and after the explosion had suspended testing at the site until a company-led investigation was complete and its regulators approved SpaceX’s corrective actions. The FAA’s comments added some clarity to the dispute that led to an angry tweet from Musk on Jan.  28 in which he accused the agency of having a “fundamentally broken regulatory structure. ” His ire against the FAA was triggered after another SpaceX test flight was delayed. Without giving much detail
column10: the FAA in a Tuesday morning email said that SpaceX was now in compliance and could proceed with another test.  Within hours
column11: the unmanned Starship SN-9 lifted off from SpaceX’s seaside launch pad at 2:25 p. m.  Tuesday in Boca Chica
column13: flew to an altitude of about 10 kilometers (6. 2 miles) -- and exploded as it attempted to land
column14: like the earlier rocket. Later in the day
column15: the agency said it will lead the investigation into the latest “landing mishap” and look for other ways to enhance safety. Meanwhile
column16: Tesla has been engaged in a long back and forth with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration over the failure of touch screens in some of its Model S and Model X vehicles.  Last month
column17: NHTSA sent a letter to Tesla saying it had determined the failures constituted a defect.  Tesla responded that it “respectfully disagrees” with the finding but will voluntarily initiate a recall.  Impacted Tesla customers received emails that said they will be notified “when the parts become available. ”“Tesla makes it very clear that they don’t think this is necessary
column18: but they are doing this to make the issue go away
column20: a former head of the agency’s Office of Defects Investigation who now runs a safety consulting business
column21: in a phone interview Tuesday.  “If NHTSA had not written the recall request letter
column22: Tesla would not have done this. ”Musk
column24: is widely heralded for disrupting the auto industry with high performance electric cars and upending Big Aerospace with reusable rockets. His companies are growing: Tesla is building two new factories in Berlin and in Austin
column26: while SpaceX -- which has contracts with the Air Force and NASA -- is rolling out Starlink
column28: to rural and remote customers across the U. S.
column29: Canada and the U. K.  There’s also the Boring Co.
column32: which is testing its brain machine interface device on monkeys and pigs and hopes to begin human trials this year. Musk’s frustration with regulators is legendary. He once hung up during a testy call with the head of the National Transportation Safety Board over Tesla’s Autopilot driver-assistance system; the NTSB was irked in part by the company’s public comments about a crash probe.  Tesla has aggressively pushed out Autopilot -- including what it calls a Full Self-Driving upgrade -- much to the consternation of some safety advocates
column33: even as driverless tech rivals like Google parent Alphabet Inc. ’s Waymo unit in recent weeks have taken pains to be more transparent and circumspect with their claims. When public health officials in California’s Alameda County ordered Tesla to close its factory last spring
column34: Musk railed against the shut down orders as “fascist” on the company’s earnings call.  And despite settling with the SEC over his failed go-private bid in 2018
column35: Musk has continued to taunt the agency
column36: referring to them as the “Shortseller Enrichment Commission. ”The settlement stripped Musk of the chairmanship of Tesla’s board for three years
column37: meaning he could potentially resume the role this fall -- just as the Biden administration is re-establishing the government’s role in oversight. (Adds detail from FAA comments in fourth and seventh paragraphs)For more articles like this

column2: it may be tough to believe what I'm about to say
column3: but here we go: Intel is currently beating AMD in CPU pricing and availability.  The result of which
column4: according to a report from Mercury Research
column5: is that AMD is actually losing market share for the first time since 2017. Off the back of its technical expertise with the Zen CPU architecture
column6: AMD has been snapping up market share these past few years.  Most recently
column7: and according to Mercury Research (via Tom's Hardware)
column8: its desktop offerings accounted for 20. 1 percent of the market.  A significant increase from 9. 9 percent back in 2016. There have been similar gains for AMD in mobile processors and
column10: in servers too.  The latter is to be expected
column12: as switching servers progresses much slower than with us fickle gaming lot on desktop. The latest numbers show that AMD's momentum has slowed a little over the course of the final three months of 2020.  Its desktop processor share shrunk by 0. 8 percent and its mobile share by 1. 2 percent compared to the previous quarter. We can speculate on reasons why
column13: but as Tom's Hardware rightly points out
column14: it's not for a lack of x86 processor sales.  In fact
column16: and AMD should be crushing it with its most impressive CPU architecture to date. Mercury Research reports that the x86 market processor grew at 20. 1 percent for the quarter.  Paired with AMD's strong growth from recent earnings reports
column17: it's understandably not as much a question of demand as it is of supply. #https://www.pcgamer.com/amd-intel-cpu-market-share-q4-2020/#aZ2sUDCAi

column2: which recently ended development of an experimental therapy for Covid-19
column3: rallied to close 39% higher on Monday after a poster on Reddit’s WallStreetBets forum called it “the most undervalued stock in the market” while another said a brewing BioWar was “about sticking it to the shorts in a massive way. ”​Biotechs with little to no revenue have long been the focus of short bets on Wall Street and could emerge as a new focal point for small-time investors railing against elite hedge funds.
